1823 // Very useful tool for identifying a single bad function compilation.
1824 // Use with a tool like `find-first-fail`: https://gitlab.com/ole.tange/tangetools/-/blob/master/find-first-fail/find-first-fail
1825 // 1. Enable ENABLE_BISECT_TOOL below.
1826 // 2. Make a new script `tmp.sh` calling a failing replay (change to use the failing replay, but don't change --extra_args):
1827 // python tests/run_replay_tests.py --filter stellar --frame 40000 --not_interactive --extra_args="-replay-fail-assert-instant -jit-precompile -jit-threads 0 -test-jit-bisect $1"
1828 // 3. Run the bisect script (may need to increase the end range if script is large, as it is based on number of functions):
1829 // bash ~/tools/find-first-fail.sh -s 0 -e 10000 -v -q bash tmp.sh
1830 // 4. For the number given, set `-test-jit-bisect` to that, and set a breakpoint
1831 // where specified in bisect_tool_should_skip. Whatever function being processed is the one to focus on.
1832 // #define ENABLE_BISECT_TOOL
1833 245844 static bool bisect_tool_should_skip()

1835 #ifdef ENABLE_BISECT_TOOL
1836 static int64_t c = 0;
1837 static int64_t x = get_flag_int("-test-jit-bisect").value();
1838 // Skip the first x calls.
1839 bool skip = 0 <= c && c < x;
1840 c++;
1841 if (!skip)
1842 // Set a breakpoint here.
1843 x = x;
1844 return skip;
1845 #else
1846 245844 return false;
1847 #endif
1848 }
